>> This means that every single
note in an octave is played.

37
00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:32.180
>> So you can see, she's color
coded the pitches of the scale.

38
00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:34.260
Now just running up the chromatic scale.

39
00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:39.767
>> These notes are then rearranged
to make a row or series,

40
00:02:39.767 --> 00:02:43.123
where each of the 12 notes is used,
and no note is played twice.

41
00:02:43.123 --> 00:02:46.012
>> The composer uses any series he or
she wishes.

42
00:02:46.012 --> 00:02:47.974
[MUSIC]

43
00:02:47.974 --> 00:02:54.254
>> The series can then be reversed
to create a different sound.

44
00:02:54.254 --> 00:02:55.764
[MUSIC]

45
00:02:55.764 --> 00:02:58.132
>> Retrograde, going backwards.

46
00:02:58.132 --> 00:03:01.046
[MUSIC]

47
00:03:01.046 --> 00:03:05.573
And the row can go backward and
forward simultaneously against itself.

48
00:03:05.573 --> 00:03:09.760
But isn't this all a little bit strange, a
little bit crazy, a little bit unmusical?

49
00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:11.580
Just modern mathematical games?

50
00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:12.451
Well, no.

51
00:03:12.451 --> 00:03:17.289
Actually, JS Bach did the same
thing in this piece from

52
00:03:17.289 --> 00:03:21.296
his musical offering back in the 1740s.

53
00:03:21.296 --> 00:03:24.941
[MUSIC]

54
00:03:24.941 --> 00:03:27.943
And this is called a crab canon,
as you can see here,

55
00:03:27.943 --> 00:03:31.300
because the crab looks forward
while walking backwards.

56
00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:37.874
The back is getting
closer to the middle now,

57
00:03:37.874 --> 00:03:42.944
the beginning of the melody is now at
the midpoint and heading toward the end,

58
00:03:42.944 --> 00:03:46.775
and my end is becoming my beginning,
my beginning my end.

59
00:03:46.775 --> 00:03:56.775
[MUSIC]

60
00:03:58.130 --> 00:04:02.056
And musicians from the Renaissance also
used these permutations of the melody,

61
00:04:02.056 --> 00:04:05.438
forward, backwards, upside down, whatever.

62
00:04:05.438 --> 00:04:11.720
So if Josquin and Bach could do it,
so too could Arnold Schoenberg.

63
00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:18.830
So let's continue with our presentation
of the permutations of the 12-tone row.

64
00:04:18.830 --> 00:04:21.590
>> Inversion is like creating
a mirror image of the original row.

65
00:04:21.590 --> 00:04:24.290
Each note of the inversion directly
matches up with the note of the series.

66
00:04:24.290 --> 00:04:28.553
Okay, if the row goes up,
the inversion goes down.

67
00:04:28.553 --> 00:04:30.583
If the row goes down,
the inversion goes up.

68
00:04:30.583 --> 00:04:32.476
[MUSIC]

69
